SIMPLE: meddle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Meddle
<hw>Med"dle`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Meddled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Meddling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>medlen</ets> to mix, OF. <ets>medler</ets>, <ets>mesler</ets>, F.
<ets>m⟦ecir⟧ler</ets>, LL. <ets>misculare</ets>, a dim. fr. L.
<ets>miscere</ets> to mix. ⟦root⟧271. See <er>Mix</er>, and cf.
<er>Medley</er>, <er>Mellay</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To mix; to mingle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>More to know⟦br⟧
Did never <qex>meddle</qex> with my thoughts.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To interest or engage one's self; to have to do; --
in a good sense.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Study to be quiet, and to <qex>meddle</qex> with your own
business.</q> <rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To interest or engage one's self unnecessarily or
impertinently, to interfere or busy one's self improperly with another's
affairs; specifically, to handle or disturb another's property without
permission; -- often followed by <ptcl>with</ptcl> or
<ptcl>in</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why shouldst thou <qex>meddle</qex> to thy hurt?</q> <rj><qau>2
Kings xiv. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The civil lawyers . . . have <qex>meddled</qex> in a matter that
belongs not to them.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To meddle and make</b></col>, <cd>to intrude one's self
into another person's concerns.</cd> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To interpose; interfere; intermeddle.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meddle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Meddle
<hw>Med"dle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To mix; to mingle.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧Wine <qex>meddled</qex> with gall.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Wyclif (Matt. xxvii. 34).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meddler</ent>⟦br⟧
